  Pre-Prep

This course is meant for complete beginners, so you don't need to have a background in video tools. However, we will be using tools like Adobe After Effects, Premiere Pro, and Photoshop for some light editing work. If you are new to these tools, no sweat, I've curated a list of some interesting information that may help you as you get ready to learn AI filmmaking.

After Effects in 10 Minutes from Ben Marriott

Ben is a good guy that is probably the best After Effects teacher in the world. This quick 10 minute video will explain how to get started with this essential tool.

Premiere Pro in 20 Minutes

This is a great introductory video to using Premiere Pro. It may seem daunting at first, but Premiere is actually pretty easy to navigate once you get the hang of it.

Photoshop in 13 Minutes

This quick video is a great way to learn Photoshop from scratch. Vince is surprisingly able to get to some intermediate-level tips in a short amount of time. I highly reccomend.

15 Great Director's Styles

This post shares some of the best styles from various directors in the industry. I recommend watching some films from these directors to get inspiration for the type of film you want to create. Know of a few styles you want to emulate in your work? Let us know about them in the chat!

A Breakdown of Analogue Film Styles

This article breaks down the stylistic differences between certain types of 35mm film. I recommend finding a style you like as it will be easier to get consistency with your prompts if you find an ideal style.
